node.title: Perseverance Rover Landing Site with John Grant

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Air and Space Museum on July 29, 2021. May be an image of drink and text.

node.text:
“One giant sip for mankind.”

Today in 1985, STS-51-F launched carrying carbonated beverages into space for the first time. The companies had to develop a can that would work in weightlessness to keep the cola fizzy without spewing out of the can. It appears that neither won the taste test however, as the astronauts said the cola was too foamy to be tasty. 

“One giant sip for mankind” was Pepsi’s slogan for the campaign.

node.text:
What's #Olympics coverage without stunning aerial views? This Goodyear Blimp control car provided overhead views of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.

That wasn't the first major sporting event for C-49 "Columbia." It also saw duty over the 1977, 1980, 1983, and 1985 Super Bowls; the 1981 and 1984 World Series; and various Rose Bowl games and parades. Apollo 15 had an all-Air Force crew: commander David Scott, command module pilot Alfred Worden, and LMP James Irwin. In fact, all three went to military academies before being selected as astronauts and later flying the Apollo 15 mission together:
👨‍🚀 CDR David Scott graduated from West Point in 1954 and became a fighter pilot and test pilot in the Air Force, logging over 5,600 hours of flying time. Apollo 15 was his third spaceflight, having previously flown on Gemini 8 and Apollo 9.
👨‍🚀 CMP Al Worden graduated from West Point in 1955 and joined the Air Force, serving as an instructor, pilot, and armament officer. He was selected by NASA as an astronaut in 1966. Apollo 15 was his first spaceflight.
👨‍🚀 LMP Jim Irwin graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy in 1951 and was commissioned in the Air Force, where he served as a test pilot. He was selected as an astronaut in 1966 and Apollo 15 was his first spaceflight.

To the Moon and back.

On this day in 1969, the Apollo 11 astronauts splashed down in the Pacific Ocean, fulfilling the second half of JFK's Moonshot: "...and returning him safely to Earth." They spent three weeks in quarantine—the first 88 hours of it in the Mobile Quarantine Facility (MQF). The astronauts greeted important visitors like President Nixon and their wives by looking through the small windows of the converted airstream trailer. The Apollo 11 MQF is on display at the Udvar-Hazy Center.

First woman at the helm of the Shuttle.

On July 23, 1999, Eileen Collins became the first female space shuttle commander aboard Space Shuttle Columbia for STS-93. She did not want to be the first-and-only, however. When Collins was asked about being the first woman to command the space shuttle, she replied "Hopefully not for long!" That came true in 2007, when Pamela Melroy commanded STS-120.

node.text:
The Sinking of Liberty Bell 7: Gus Grissom’s Near-Fatal Mission
60 years ago today, Virgil I. “Gus” Grissom flew the second NASA Mercury-Redstone mission. That trip, nearly identical to Alan Shepard’s a few months before, almost ended in disaster. Grissom’s capsule, Liberty Bell 7, sank after the successful splashdown in the Atlantic, and Grissom came close to drowning.
Up until splashdown, everything worked normally, his capsule’s parachutes deployed, and he landed in the ocean 15 minutes and 37 seconds after liftoff. After the  hatch of the spacecraft suddenly blew off and seawater began pouring over the hatch rim, Grissom threw himself out the hatch and swam away from the sinking spacecraft. The helicopter crew, thinking he was ok and following their training, moved in to hook on to the sinking Liberty Bell 7. But the water flowing into the capsule made it too heavy for the helicopter, which at one point had all three wheels in the water.
Grissom, meanwhile, found himself slowly sinking too, as water leaked in through the oxygen inlet of his spacesuit. Blasted by the rotor wash, Grissom waved frantically to the helicopter. After Liberty Bell 7 sank, and fortunately before Grissom did, the crew came back and lowered the sling. The wet and exhausted astronaut was taken back to the carrier.
Read our full story about the sinking of Liberty Bell 7 (and discover the punny name Grissom gave his Gemini 3 capsule as a result) by visiting the link in our bio.

node.text: Apollo 11 isn't the only Michael Collins mission celebrating an anniversary right now. 55 years ago this week, the Gemini 10 mission was taking place with astronauts Michael Collins and John Young. It was the first spaceflight to rendezvous with two different vehicles in orbit (Agena Target Vehicles 10 and 8). The Gemini 10 capsule docked with Agena 10, and Collins performed an EVA to travel to Agena 8.

80 years ago today, the first class of Black aviation cadets who would become the Tuskegee Airmen began training at Tuskegee Army Air Field.
The Tuskegee Army Air Field became the vital center for training African Americans to fly fighter and bomber aircraft during World War II. Serving in the 99th Fighter Squadron and the 332nd Fighter Group, the Tuskegee Airmen made a pioneering contribution to the war and the subsequent drive to end racial segregation in the American armed forces. That first class of pilots graduated from the Advanced Flying School in 1942.
